	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				 I suppose his death is due some respect, if only to make certain people feel better. Just like the deaths of however many people were slain in the Septembre eleventh thing should only be honoured to make those alive experience less pain or more pleasure. But in the objective universe, we're just meaningless clumps of matter. Our deaths do not matter, our lives do not matter. Our real lives and our everquest lives are not all that different. One is just much more complex and less involving. It's just a computer game, people say. Well, this is just a flesh and blood game. *shrugs* The closest things to things that supposedly matter are pain and pleasure, for they are, without anything beside them, evoke a negative or a positive response. So if his death matters little to me, as it does, and I laugh at it, as I did, I am simply harvesting pleasure. The only reason I would not want to do that is the pain my harvesting of pleasure might cause others. Not that others' pain matters to me as much as my pleasure. But I do try to avoid it. His death changes nothing. Our meaningless toil goes on.<BR>
<BR>
Now, as for everyone's comments about Everquest addiction -- yes, I am addicted. Or at least have nothing better to do with my time. I am liked by almost everyone I interact with, yet I never had a girl-friend and am anti-social. So what? Some day we shall all be decaying dust. I shall play Everquest and do drugs for pleasure if I find nothing more fulfilling (and I certainly wish to), as I have not so far.<BR>
<BR>
My advice for everyone (and I do not claim to be wise, but I've noticed a few things) is to glean pleasure, laugh at pain, suffer quietly when you have to, and die painlessly in the end. *shrugs*<BR>
<BR>
Zooh Flesheater &lt;Church of Apathy&gt;<BR>
<BR>
Tallon Zek
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
